  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. These laws and conventions establish frameworks for countries to cooperate in preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering. Here's a breakdown of some of the key ones:\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988 Vienna Convention):** This convention was one of the first major international efforts to address money laundering. It requires states to criminalize the laundering of proceeds derived from drug trafficking offenses.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000 Palermo Convention):** This convention expands the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug-related crimes to include proceeds from a wider range of transnational organized crimes, such as trafficking in persons, smuggling of migrants, and corruption.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003 Merida Convention):** This convention focuses on combating corruption and includes provisions on preventing and criminalizing the laundering of proceeds derived from corruption.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** While not a treaty or convention, the FATF Recommendations are the international standard for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. The FATF is an inter-governmental body that develops and promotes policies to protect the global financial system. Its 40 Recommendations are widely adopted by countries around the world and serve as a benchmark for assessing national anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CTF) regimes.\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990 Strasbourg Convention) and Revised Convention (2005):** These conventions aim to facilitate international cooperation in investigating, prosecuting, and confiscating the proceeds of crime.\n\n**Key Aspects Covered by These Laws and Conventions:**\n\n*   **Criminalization of Money Laundering:** Requiring countries to establish money laundering as a criminal offense in their national laws.\n*   **Customer Due Diligence (CDD):** Mandating financial institutions to identify and verify the identities of their customers.\n*   **Record Keeping:** Requiring financial institutions to maintain records of transactions for a specified period.\n*   **Suspicious Transaction Reporting (STR):** Obligating financial institutions to report suspicious transactions to relevant authorities.\n*   **International Cooperation:** Facilitating the exchange of information and mutual legal assistance between countries in money laundering investigations and prosecutions.\n*   **Confiscation of Assets:** Enabling the seizure and confiscation of assets derived from or involved in money laundering.\n\nIt is important to note that each country implements these international laws and conventions through its own national laws and regulations. The effectiveness of international efforts to combat money laundering depends on the commitment and cooperation of individual countries.",
